    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-03-04T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-03-04T07:00:00-05:00" n="185"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1545</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-04T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 4, 1915, 1 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received March, 5, 3.40 p. m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1753. Informed on good authority that <persName corresp="#p_ZAFM1"
                        >Zimmermann</persName> and Chancellor were in favor of accepting American
                    proposal without change but that all matters now really in military and naval
                    hands and that Admiral <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">von Tirpitz</persName> did
                    not want England to accept our proposal and therefore added conditions of
                    Declaration of London so as to make acceptance impossible. Chancellor not as
                    popular or in such high favor with Emperor as <persName corresp="#p_TAPFV1">Von
                        Tirpitz</persName> who with <persName corresp="#p_FEGASV1"
                        >Falkenhayn</persName>, Chief of General Staff, decides everything. Emperor
                    is very bitter against America on account of delivery of arms.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
